This also happens when using the ESLint API:

```js
// test.mjs
import { ESLint } from 'eslint';

const eslint = new ESLint({
    ignore: false,
    overrideConfigFile: true,
    baseConfig: {
        ignores: ['index.js'],
        rules: {
          'no-undef': 'error',
        },
    }
});

const [result] = await eslint.lintText('foo', { filePath: 'index.js' });
console.log(result);
```

Running the above code:

```console
$ node test.mjs
{
  filePath: '.../project/index.js',
  messages: [
    {
      ruleId: 'no-undef',
      severity: 2,
      message: "'foo' is not defined.",
      line: 1,
      column: 1,
      nodeType: 'Identifier',
      messageId: 'undef',
      endLine: 1,
      endColumn: 4
    }
  ],
  suppressedMessages: [],
  errorCount: 1,
  fatalErrorCount: 0,
  warningCount: 0,
  fixableErrorCount: 0,
  fixableWarningCount: 0,
  source: 'foo',
  usedDeprecatedRules: [Getter]
}
```

@nzakas do you remember if this was intentional? By looking at the code, it does seem intentional:

https://github.com/eslint/eslint/blob/96607d0581845fab19f832cd435547f9da960733/lib/config/flat-config-array.js#L135-L155

But there are no test cases to confirm the intent (when I replace `!config.files` with `Object.keys(config).length === 1`, which would mean "remove `ignores` only if it's the only key in the config object", all tests are still passing).
